=== Lesson 28-2 (Step-by-Step Approach) ===

 {"type":"h3","text":"Step-by-Step Approach"}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 1: Create a Passage Blueprint"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"After reading, create a quick, high-level map of the passage's structure..."}
 {"type":"list","items":["**Example Blueprint:**","Para 1: Introduces a common theory.","Para 2: Presents evidence that challenges this theory.","Para 3: Proposes an alternative theory.","Para 4: Discusses the implications of the alternative theory."]}

{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "The Passage Blueprint method is the best structural teaching tool in any of the small RC modules. The example blueprint is concrete and demonstrates exactly what 'functional summary' means.", "variant": "comment" }

 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 2: Match Your Blueprint to the Answer Choices"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Systematically compare the structural description in each answer choice to the blueprint you created..."}
+{{+**Missing:** Add a matching checklist: (1) Does the answer match the number of structural parts? (2) Does it correctly identify each part's function? (3) Does it use accurate verbs for each part's role?+}}
+{{+**Try this:** Attempt the question before reading the analysis below.+}}
+{{+Add a question-card here demonstrating the blueprint method end-to-end.+}}
 {"type":"hr"}
 {"type":"h3","text":"If You Get Stuck Between Two Choices..."}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Tie-Breaker #1: Focus on the Verbs"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Isolate the primary action verbs in your final two choices (e.g., \"refuting\" vs. \"qualifying,\" \"contrasting\" vs. \"evaluating\")..."}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Tie-Breaker #2: Check the Scope and Emphasis"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Re-read your two final choices. Does one of them describe a minor, supporting part of the passage as if it were a main structural component?..."}

{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "Both tie-breakers are precise and target real error sources. 'Focus on the Verbs' is especially valuable -- verb precision is the deciding factor on most Approach questions.", "variant": "comment" }
